  "text": "It is clear that most of these definitions, with the exception of the definition of [CITATION_1] , include aspects of life dimensions other than the emotional life dimension. They therefore do not clearly distinguish between the emotional and other life dimensions. Some EI specialists define EI in a narrow sense, but broaden the concept when applying it in developing EI. Le Roux and De Klerk (2003, p. 10) , for instance, define EI in terms of abilities: Emotional intelligence is a type of personal and social intelligence, which includes the following: l the ability to perceive, recognise, understand and react to the feelings of yourself and those of others (emotional awareness); l the ability to distinguish between various feelings and to name them (emotional literacy); l the ability to express and control your feelings appropriately (emotional control); (Then they start broadening their definition) l the ability to listen to others, to have empathy with them, and to communicate effectively in terms of emotions and thoughts, and",
